John Edward: Languages skills essential for world citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent status in academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with a new series of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other initiatives of the entire community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for continuing and higher education, the career chosen by them and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust bonds with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year, we can conclude that languages are on top of the ranking list, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated to SCIS, shows that 72 percent of the students achieved a high score ("A") in Mandarin, while 72 percent of the students achieved an A as well as 69 percent of students in French and 63 percent of students in Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now rated as professionally as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
A study by the British Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17% of the obstacles to filling vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
So language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
Now that more and more job vacancies require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career that a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Direct communication with foreign people automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage to competition.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language that was above 10%, with a total of 15%.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today's children.
Several languages, particularly those of emerging economies, will offer children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools themselves choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the United Kingdom when they look ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest is, there will always be different languages to choose in independent schools, with teachers specialised in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot be denied at the moment that languages in a global business environment remain vital to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's an ugly bee.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
