Harvard students take a course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, trying to fight the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night long and drink a lot of caffeine.
A professor found that the students of the world's largest university often have no idea of the basic principles to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course. As far as he knows, this is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a talk about the influence of lack of sleep on learning.
"At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, "Why am I only hearing this in my last year?"
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep is, what surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
In the course, which is organised for the first time this year, the students explain the basic principles of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was established that students had a severe sleep shortage during the week.
The course takes one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the parts, the students see an image of a dormitory room, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise machines and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine at bedtime.
In another part, participants are told how long-term sleep shortages increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Through a map of the campus, with interactive pictograms, participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine.
‘We know that this will not change the conduct of the students immediately.
But we think that they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know the consequences of cigarette choice on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of ferrets on a night study still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and increasing pressure on students, sleep shortages are an increasing problem.
Sustaining sufficient sleep, of good quality, must be the ‘secret weapon’ of the student to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to prepare the course. He had attended the professor’s class last year when he studied at Harvard in his first year.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and had inspired him to ensure that the course became available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before they come to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm for their bedtime, and not just an alarm to stand up. They should also be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronics screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, making it difficult for you to fall asleep.
