The inventor of the World Wide Web is planning a new internet to tackle Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, starts a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project of the technology legend, is a company based on the open source platform Solid from Berners-Lee.
Solid offers users the possibility to choose where their data are stored and which persons have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee grabbed that 'world domination' is the leading thought behind Inrupt.
"We have to do this now," he said about the startup.
"This is a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology to enable people to make their own 'personal online data storage' or POD.
Lists of contacts, activity lists, an agenda, a music library and other personal and professional tools can be stored here.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available together via one browser and all at the same time.
What makes POD unique is the fact that it depends entirely on the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this 'personal empowerment through data'.
According to CEO John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company provides the resources, processes and skills needed to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers contracted to work on the project, and a community of voluntary programmers.
From this week, developers of technology around the world can make their own decentralised apps with the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team will not have any conversations with "Facebook and Google about introducing or not a complete transformation that puts all their business models at their head at once".
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post published on Medium Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that the "mission (van Inrupt) is to supply the commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web, which is built on Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the internet when he set up the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
After the start of Inrupt Berners-Lee will remain as founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am incredibly optimistic about this new web era," added Berners-Lee.
