National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
New research carried out on a estate in the Scottish highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
The hope is that the findings will give new light to the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown big-eared bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed on key locations around the estate to track the activities of bats throughout the season.
NTS employees and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the cries of the bat and what kind of action does.
Next, a map of the habitat and a report are produced to make a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation consultant, hopes that the results show which habitat areas are the most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of pastures and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleep and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, such as flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
Because of their night hunting habits, however, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares on land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts who carry out regular surveys, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threeave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of bats live in Scotland.
Landscape manager David Thompson says that the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threeave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But there is so much not yet known about bats and therefore the work that we do here and at other locations will help us to understand better what they need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work was carried out, because the possibly unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their boys, possibly eliminating a full local population.
Bats are a protected animal species and it is illegal to kill them, to stumble or to disturb them, or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our species we just don't know how their populations are doing."
